a digitally connected but fiercely competitive, highly individualized world?Based upon fieldwork at an ordinary London school, The Class examines young people's experiences of growing up and learning in a digital world. In this original and engaging study, Livingstone and Sefton-Green explore youth values, teenagers' perspectives on their futures, and their tactics for facing the opportunities and challenges that lie ahead. The authors follow the students as they move across their different social worlds-in school, at home, and with their friends, engaging in a range of activities from video games to drama clubs and music lessons. By portraying the texture of the students' everyday lives, The Class seeks to understand how the structures of social class and cultural capital shape the development of personal interests, relationships and autonomy. Providing insights into how young people's social, digital, and learning networks enable or disempower them, Livingstone and Sefton-Green reveal that the experience of disconnections and blocked pathways is often more common than that of connections and new opportunities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspectszEnglandzLondon. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aInformation societyxSocial aspectszEnglandzLondon. 0aInformation societyxSocial aspects. 0aInternet and teenagersxSocial aspectszEnglandzLondon. 0aInternet and teenagersxSocial aspects. 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 0aTechnology and youthxSocial aspectszEnglandzLondon. 0aTechnology and youthxSocial aspects. 0aTeenagersxAttitudes. 0aTeenagersxEducationzEnglandzLondon. 0aTeenagersxEducation. 0aTeenagersxSocial conditions. 0aTeenagerszEnglandzLondonxAttitudes. 0aTeenagerszEnglandzLondonxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 a